      <label>Designations</label>
  
                <p><strong>Designations by the U.S. Government:</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><th colspan="2"><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-us.jpg" /></th></tr><tr><td>October 8, 1997: Secretary of State designates Palestine Islamic Jihad - Shaqaqi Faction as a Foreign Terrorist Organization.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Chapter 6. Foreign Terrorist Organizations,&rdquo; U.S. Department of State, May 30, 2013, <a href="http://www.state.gov/j/ct/rls/crt/2012/209989.htm">http://www.state.gov/j/ct/rls/crt/2012/209989.htm</a>.</span></td></tr></tbody></table><p><strong>Designations by Foreign Governments and Organizations:</strong></p><table><tbody><tr><td><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-australia.jpg" /> Australia&mdash;listed PIJ as a terrorist organization on December 21, 2001.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Consolidated list,&rdquo; Australian Government, accessed March 2, 2015, <a href="http://www.dfat.gov.au/sanctions/consolidated-list.html">http://www.dfat.gov.au/sanctions/consolidated-list.html</a>.</span></td><td><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-canada.jpg" />Canada&mdash;listed Palestinian Islamic Jihad (PIJ) as a terrorist entity on November 27, 2002.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Currently Listed Entities,&rdquo; Public Safety Canada, accessed March 3, 2015, <a href="http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#2040">http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#http://www.publicsafety.gc.ca/cnt/ntnl-scrt/cntr-trrrsm/lstd-ntts/crrnt-lstd-ntts-eng.aspx#2040</a>.</span></td></tr><tr><td><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-eu.jpg" /> EU&mdash;listed Palestinian Islamic Jihad (PIJ) as groups and entities involved in terrorist acts on December 27, 2001.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Council Common Position of 27 December 2001 on the application of specific measures to combat terrorism,&rdquo; EUR-LEX, accessed March 3, 2015, <a href="http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:32001E0931&amp;from=EN">http://eur-lex.europa.eu/legal-content/EN/TXT/HTML/?uri=CELEX:32001E0931&amp;from=EN</a>.</span></td><td><img src="/sites/default/files/flag-newzealand.jpg" /> New Zealand&mdash;listed Palestinian Islamic Jihad (PIJ) as a terrorist entity on October 11, 2010.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Lists associated with Resolution 1373,&rdquo; New Zealand Police, accessed March 3, 2015, <a href="http://www.police.govt.nz/advice/personal-community/counterterrorism/designated-entities/lists-associated-with-resolution-1373">http://www.police.govt.nz/advice/personal-community/counterterrorism/designated-entities/lists-associated-with-resolution-1373</a>.</span></td></tr><tr><td><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-uk.jpg" />United Kingdom&mdash;listed Palestinian Islamic Jihad - Shaqaqi (PIJ) as an organization believed to be concerned in terrorism in March 2001.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Proscribed Terrorist Organizations,&rdquo; UK Home Office, last updated February 3, 2015, <a href="https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/400902/Proscription-20150123.pdf">https://www.gov.uk/government/uploads/system/uploads/attachment_data/file/400902/Proscription-20150123.pdf</a>.</span></td><td>&nbsp;</td></tr></tbody></table>        </div>


<div class="field field-type-text-long">
  
      <label>Associations</label>
  
                <p><strong>Ties to Extremist Entities designated by the U.S. or foreign governments:</strong></p>

<table>
	<tbody><tr>
		<td width="325"><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-iran.jpg" />Iran and the <a href="http://www.counterextremism.com/threat/islamic-revolutionary-guards-corps">Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC)</a><br />PIJ&rsquo;s founders modeled the group&rsquo;s Islamist objectives under the influence of Iran&rsquo;s 1979 Islamic Revolution. Iran is PIJ&rsquo;s primary source of financial support, according to the U.S. State Department.<span class="footnote">Holly Fletcher, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; Council on Foreign Relations, April 10, 2008, <a href="http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984">http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984</a>.</span> A 1998 lawsuit against Iran in U.S. federal court revealed that the Islamic Republic allocated $2 million in its annual budget to PIJ.<span class="footnote">Richard Sisk, &ldquo;Terror Victim&rsquo;s Dad Wins $247M Lawsuit Vs. Iran,&rdquo; <em>New York Daily News</em>, March 12, 1998, <a href="http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/terror-victim-dad-wins-247m-lawsuit-iran-article-1.789077">http://www.nydailynews.com/archives/news/terror-victim-dad-wins-247m-lawsuit-iran-article-1.789077</a>.</span> That number has since skyrocketed&mdash;in late 2013, PIJ sources revealed that the terror group received about $3 million per month from Iran.<span class="footnote">Hazem Balousha, &ldquo;Islamic Jihad May Respond If Israel Enters Syria War,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, September 2, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/islamic-jihad-syria-us-strike.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/islamic-jihad-syria-us-strike.html</a>.</span> A February 2014 report by Ali Nourizadeh, director of the Center for Iranian Studies in London, stated that Iran provides PIJ with $100 to $150 million annually.<span class="footnote">Joshua Levitt, &ldquo;Expert: Hamas Received $2 Billion from Iran; Islamic Jihad Gets $150 Million Annually,&rdquo; <em>Algemeiner</em>, February 11, 2014, <a href="http://www.algemeiner.com/2014/02/11/expert-hamas-received-2-billion-from-iran-islamic-jihad-gets-150-million-annually/">http://www.algemeiner.com/2014/02/11/expert-hamas-received-2-billion-from-iran-islamic-jihad-gets-150-million-annually/</a>.</span><br /><br />According to PIJ spokesman Daoud Shihab, &ldquo;all of the weapons in Gaza are provided by Iran,&rdquo; and &ldquo;everyone knows that Iran is financing&rdquo; PIJ.<span class="footnote">Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad: Iran Supplies All Weapons in Gaza,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, May 14, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html</a>.</span> In February 2014, a group of PIJ leaders, including Ramadan Shallah, made what Shihab called a &ldquo;routine visit&rdquo; to Tehran, which &ldquo;still supports resistance factions.&rdquo;<span class="footnote">Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Hamas Isolated as Iran Boosts Ties with Islamic Jihad, Fatah,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, February 12, 2014, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/02/islamic-jihad-fatah-hamas-iran-palestinians.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/02/islamic-jihad-fatah-hamas-iran-palestinians.html</a>.</span><br /><br />PIJ also receives aid through Iran&rsquo;s Islamic Revolutionary Guards Corps (IRGC).<span class="footnote">Holly Fletcher, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; Council on Foreign Relations, April 10, 2008, <a href="http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984">http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984</a>.</span> The IRGC is Iran&rsquo;s primary instrument for spreading the Islamic Revolution abroad and has acted as a conduit between the Iranian regime and PIJ. The IRGC provides PIJ with weapons, training, and funding. It reportedly began sending support after the PIJ was exiled to Lebanon in 1987.<span class="footnote">Holly Fletcher, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; Council on Foreign Relations, April 10, 2008, <a href="http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984">http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984</a>.</span><br /><br />Since the beginning of the 2011 Syrian civil war, Iran has reportedly increased its support of PIJ at the expense of Hamas. Unlike Hamas, Iran supports Syria&rsquo;s Assad regime and PIJ has noticeably maintained its base in Damascus, Syria (although PIJ otherwise appears to be neutral).<span class="footnote">Fares Akram, &ldquo;In Gaza, Iran Finds an Ally More Agreeable Than Hamas,&rdquo; <em>New York Times</em>, July 31, 2013, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/world/middleeast/in-gaza-iran-finds-a-closer-ally-than-hamas.html">http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/world/middleeast/in-gaza-iran-finds-a-closer-ally-than-hamas.html</a>; Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad: Iran Supplies All Weapons in Gaza,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, May 14, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html</a>.</span> In 2013, Iran sent $2 million worth of food aid to Gaza during the Islamic holy month of Ramadan, entrusting members of PIJ with distribution. This aid bore stamps with the Palestinian flag alongside the PIJ logo and the Iranian flag.<span class="footnote">Fares Akram, &ldquo;In Gaza, Iran Finds an Ally More Agreeable Than Hamas,&rdquo; <em>New York Times</em>, July 31, 2013, <a href="http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/world/middleeast/in-gaza-iran-finds-a-closer-ally-than-hamas.html">http://www.nytimes.com/2013/08/01/world/middleeast/in-gaza-iran-finds-a-closer-ally-than-hamas.html</a>.</span><br /><br />International Arabic-language newspaper <em>Asharq Al-Awsat</em> reported in 2012 that PIJ&rsquo;s Syria-based leadership had relocated to Iran but continued to enjoy positive ties with their Syrian patrons. However, a PIJ official denied that report, claiming &ldquo;relations between [PIJ] and the Syrian government are excellent, unlike Hamas,&rdquo;<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Islamic Jihad Leadership Relocates to Iran,&rdquo; <em>Asharq Al-Awsat</em> (London), July 22, 2012, <a href="http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265">http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265</a>.</span> whose leadership left Syria after refusing to support the Assad regime during the Syrian civil war. Official representatives of the group are also stationed elsewhere in the Middle East,<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Country Reports on Terrorism 2013: Chapter 6. Foreign Terrorist Organizations,&rdquo; U.S. Department of State, April 30, 2014, <a href="http://www.state.gov/j/ct/rls/crt/2013/224829.htm">http://www.state.gov/j/ct/rls/crt/2013/224829.htm</a>.</span> including Iran.<span class="footnote">Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Hamas Isolated as Iran Boosts Ties with Islamic Jihad, Fatah,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, February 12, 2014, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/02/islamic-jihad-fatah-hamas-iran-palestinians.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2014/02/islamic-jihad-fatah-hamas-iran-palestinians.html</a>; &ldquo;Islamic Jihad: Israeli Attacks on Gaza Backfired,&rdquo; Tasnim News Agency, July 15, 2014, <a href="http://www.tasnimnews.com/english/Home/Single/432079">http://www.tasnimnews.com/english/Home/Single/432079l</a>.</span><br /><br />After a year of decreased funding, the IRGC reportedly restored its relations with PIJ in May 2016 with an annual allocation of $70 million. The allocation followed a visit to Tehran by a PIJ delegation the previous month. As part of the agreement, Qasem Soleimani, head of the IRGC&rsquo;s Quds Force, reportedly appointed Khaled Mansour commander of PIJ&rsquo;s Quds Brigades in Gaza.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Iran resumes funding for Palestinian Islamic Jihad: report,&rdquo; i24 News, May 25, 2016, <a href="https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/middle-east/114490-160525-iran-resumes-funding-for-palestinian-islamic-jihad-group-report">https://www.i24news.tv/en/news/international/middle-east/114490-160525-iran-resumes-funding-for-palestinian-islamic-jihad-group-report</a>.</span></td>
		<td width="325"><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-hamas.jpg" /><a href="http://www.counterextremism.com/threat/hamas">Hamas</a><br />PIJ and Hamas collaborate militarily in order to fight Israel. During the first and second Palestinian intifadas, Hamas and PIJ claimed joint responsibility for a handful of attacks, including an April 9, 1995 suicide bombing that killed seven Israeli soldiers and an American.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Major Bomb Attacks Since 1993 Peace Accord,&rdquo; Fox News, December 2, 2001, <a href="http://www.foxnews.com/story/2001/12/02/major-bomb-attacks-since-13-peace-accord">http://www.foxnews.com/story/2001/12/02/major-bomb-attacks-since-13-peace-accord/</a>.</span> The groups continued coordinated attacks after the end of the second intifada and after Hamas seized control of the Gaza Strip in 2007. In November 2012, for example, PIJ and Hamas jointly bombed a Tel Aviv bus, wounding 29 people.<span class="footnote">Gil Cohen, &ldquo;Israel Arrests Hamas, Islamic Jihad Cell behind Tel Aviv Bus Bomb,&rdquo; <em>Haaretz</em> (Tel Aviv), November 22, 2012, <a href="http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/israel-arrests-hamas-islamic-jihad-cell-behind-tel-aviv-bus-bomb-1.479958">http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/israel-arrests-hamas-islamic-jihad-cell-behind-tel-aviv-bus-bomb-1.479958</a>.</span><br /><br />After Hamas&rsquo;s falling out with Iran in 2012, relations between Hamas and PIJ also degraded. Fighters from the two organizations clashed amid accusations that Hamas was targeting PIJ. In September 2013, however, the two terror groups announced plans to form a new joint command to create a better political atmosphere in Gaza.<span class="footnote">Elhanan Miller, &ldquo;Hamas and Islamic Jihad to Form Joint Command,&rdquo; Times of Israel, September 17, 2013, <a href="http://www.timesofisrael.com/hamas-and-islamic-jihad-to-form-joint-command/">http://www.timesofisrael.com/hamas-and-islamic-jihad-to-form-joint-command/</a>.</span><br /><br />In March 2014, PIJ fired a round of mortars into Israel, prompting an Israeli strike that killed three PIJ commanders. In retaliation, PIJ launched at least 130 locally made rockets into Israel as part of a military operation called Breaking the Silence, reportedly in coordination with Hamas.<span class="footnote">Hani Ibrahim, &ldquo;Hamas&rsquo; Growing Rivalry with Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; <em>Al Akhbar English</em> (Beirut), April 16, 2014, <a href="http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/hamas%E2%80%99-growing-rivalry-islamic-jihad">http://english.al-akhbar.com/content/hamas%E2%80%99-growing-rivalry-islamic-jihad</a>.</span> PIJ and Hamas also jointly launched rockets at Israel during Israel&rsquo;s summer 2014 conflict with Hamas.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Hamas, Jihad claim joint attacks on Israeli cities,&rdquo; Ma&rsquo;an News Agency, July 15, 2014, <a href="http://www.maannews.com/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?id=713412">http://www.maannews.com/eng/ViewDetails.aspx?id=713412</a>.</span> PIJ and Hamas have since continued to coordinate politically and militarily.<span class="footnote">Yaniv Kubovich, &ldquo;Analysis Iran's Fighting Force in Gaza, Calling and Firing the Shots: This Is Islamic Jihad in Palestine,&rdquo; <em>Haaretz</em>, June 17, 2018, <a href="https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/.premium-what-is-islamic-jihad-in-palestine-iran-s-fighting-force-in-gaza-calling-and-firing-the-shots-1.6158730">https://www.haaretz.com/middle-east-news/iran/.premium-what-is-islamic-jihad-in-palestine-iran-s-fighting-force-in-gaza-calling-and-firing-the-shots-1.6158730</a>; &ldquo;Hamas meets with Islamic Jihad&rsquo;s leadership, concludes with unified stances,&rdquo; Hamas, November 2, 2018, <a href="http://hamas.ps/en/post/1660/hamas-meets-with-islamic-jihad%E2%80%99s-leadership-concludes-with-unified-stances">http://hamas.ps/en/post/1660/hamas-meets-with-islamic-jihad%E2%80%99s-leadership-concludes-with-unified-stances</a>.</span> The two groups announced in December 2019 they would join forces against Israel in the next round of conflict with the Jewish state.<span class="footnote">Khaled Abu Toameh, &ldquo;Hamas, Islamic Jihad agree to stand together in future fight with Israel,&rdquo; <em>Jerusalem Post</em>, December 20, 2019, <a href="https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Hamas-PIJ-agree-to-stand-together-in-future-confrontation-with-Israel-611458">https://www.jpost.com/Arab-Israeli-Conflict/Hamas-PIJ-agree-to-stand-together-in-future-confrontation-with-Israel-611458</a>.</span></td>
		</tr><tr>
		<td width="325"><img src="/sites/default/files/flag-hezbollah2.jpg" /><a href="http://www.counterextremism.com/threat/hezbollah">Hezbollah</a><br />In 1987, PIJ was exiled from Gaza to Lebanon. There, the group reportedly began cooperating with Hezbollah and began training under Iran&rsquo;s Islamic Revolutionary Guard Corps.<span class="footnote">Holly Fletcher, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; Council on Foreign Relations, April 10, 2008, <a href="http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984">http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984</a>.</span><br /><br />In July 2014, masked members of PIJ were filmed thanking Hezbollah, particularly its Secretary-General Hassan Nasrallah, for Hezbollah&rsquo;s &ldquo;stance and support, be it with financial, military or moral support.&rdquo;<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad Thanks Iran and Hezbollah,&rdquo; Iran English Radio, July 14, 2014, <a href="http://english.irib.ir/galleries/item/191912">http://english.irib.ir/galleries/item/191912</a>.</span></td>
		<td width="325"><img src="/sites/default/files/flag-aambrigade2.jpg" />Al Aqsa Martyrs&rsquo; Brigade<br />PIJ and the Al Aqsa Martyrs&rsquo; Brigade, the armed faction of Fatah, have carried out a handful of joint terror attacks against Israeli civilians. Examples include an April 2006 suicide bombing at a Tel Aviv sandwich stand that killed 11 people<span class="footnote">&ldquo;TIMELINE: Recent Bomb and Shooting Attacks against Israelis,&rdquo; Haaretz (Tel Aviv), November 21, 2012, <a href="http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/timeline-recent-bomb-and-shooting-attacks-against-israelis-1.479592">http://www.haaretz.com/news/diplomacy-defense/timeline-recent-bomb-and-shooting-attacks-against-israelis-1.479592</a>.</span> and a January 2007 suicide attack on an Eilat bakery that killed three.<span class="footnote">Holly Fletcher, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad,&rdquo; Council on Foreign Relations, April 10, 2008, <a href="http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984">http://www.cfr.org/israel/palestinian-islamic-jihad/p15984</a>.</span></td>
		</tr></tbody>
</table>

<p><strong>Ties to other entities:</strong></p>

<table>
	<tbody><tr>
		<td><img src="/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-syria.jpg" />Syria<br />PIJ has been based in Damascus since 1989. An anonymous PIJ source told London&rsquo;s <em>Asharq Al-Awsat</em> in July 2012 that the PIJ leadership fled Syria for Iran,<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Islamic Jihad Leadership Relocates to Iran,&rdquo; <em>Asharq Al-Awsat</em> (London), July 22, 2012, <a href="http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265">http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265</a>.</span> though PIJ officially denied that it had abandoned its base in Syria.<span class="footnote">&ldquo;Islamic Jihad Leadership Relocates to Iran,&rdquo; <em>Asharq Al-Awsat</em> (London), July 22, 2012, <a href="http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265">http://www.aawsat.net/2012/07/article55241265</a>.</span> Despite Iranian support for PIJ and Syria, PIJ has otherwise appeared to remain neutral in the Syrian civil war.<span class="footnote">Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad: Iran Supplies All Weapons in Gaza,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, May 14, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html</a>.</span> According to PIJ spokesperson Daoud Shihab, &ldquo;Palestine is greater than all axes, and we do not accept to be part of the [Syria] conflict.&rdquo;<span class="footnote">Asmaa al-Ghoul, &ldquo;Palestinian Islamic Jihad: Iran Supplies All Weapons in Gaza,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, May 14, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulseen/originals/2013/05/gaza-islamic-jihad-and-iranian-arms.html</a>.</span> PIJ has, however, threatened to respond if Israel involves itself in the Syrian civil war.<span class="footnote">Hazem Balousha, &ldquo;Islamic Jihad May Respond If Israel Enters Syria War,&rdquo; <em>Al-Monitor</em>, September 2, 2013, <a href="http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/islamic-jihad-syria-us-strike.html">http://www.al-monitor.com/pulse/originals/2013/09/islamic-jihad-syria-us-strike.html</a>.</span></td>
		<td><img src="http://www.counterextremism.com/sites/default/themes/bricktheme/stylesheets/images/flag-qatar.jpg" />Qatar<br />A U.S. lawsuit filed in June 2020 alleged Qatar provided funding to PIJ and Hamas through three Qatari financial institutions, the Qatar Charity, Masraf Al Rayan, and Qatar National Bank. The Qatar Charity is a member of the U.S.-sanctioned Union of Good charity network. All three institutions have links to members of the Qatari royal family. The plaintiffs are friends and family members of 10 U.S. citizens who died in terror attacks in Israel carried out by PIJ and Hamas. The lawsuit alleges Qatar Charity allegedly worked with Masraf Al Rayan bank and Qatar National Bank to forward Hamas and PIJ millions of dollars. It further accuses the Qatari government of coopting &ldquo;several institutions that it dominates and controls to funnel coveted U.S. dollars (the chosen currency of Middle East terrorist networks) to Hamas and PIJ under the false guise of charitable donations.&rdquo;<span class="footnote">Ray Hanania, &ldquo;Lawsuit names Qatar&rsquo;s royal family in killings of 10 Americans in Israel,&rdquo; Arab News, June 11, 2020, <a href="https://www.arabnews.com/node/1688051/middle-east">https://www.arabnews.com/node/1688051/middle-east</a>; Adam Kredo, &ldquo;Lawsuit Alleges Qatar Secretly Financed Terror Attacks that Killed Americans,&rdquo; <em>Washington Free Beacon</em>, June 10, 2020, <a href="https://freebeacon.com/national-security/lawsuit-alleges-qatar-secretly-financed-terror-attacks-that-killed-americans/">https://freebeacon.com/national-security/lawsuit-alleges-qatar-secretly-financed-terror-attacks-that-killed-americans/</a>.</span></td>
		</tr></tbody>
</table>
        </div>
